Analysis of RNAseq expressions of EÂµ-Myc_dCas9a-SAM and B-All samples

Goknur Giner

2022-06-29

1 Backgroud

In this report, we explored the expression profiles of the genes that are differentially expressed between EÂµ-Myc/dCas9a-SAM and B-All samples. The EÂµ-Myc/dCas9a-SAM and B-ALL RNA-seq experiments are sequenced using Illumina NextSeq 2000 and HiSeq 2000 platforms, respectively, as paired-end 100 bp.

2 EÂµ-Myc/dCas9a-SAM data preparation

2.1 Aligning and counting the samples

To align the EÂµ-Myc/dCas9a-SAM samples and count the reads, we used Rsubread version 2.2.6 and BioConductor version 3.11.1. Below are the details.

> writeLines(readLines("./scripts/01_align.R"))
date <- Sys.Date()
sink(paste0(date, "-align.log"), split = TRUE)
library(BiocVersion) # load this to view the version in sessionInfo
library(Rsubread)
R1 <- dir(full.names=TRUE, path="/stornext/Bioinf/data/bioinf-data/Papenfuss_lab/projects/ginerg_papenfuss_lab/Github_projects/SDiepstraten_2021_05_14/fastqfiles/", pattern="*_R1")
R2 <- dir(full.names=TRUE, path="/stornext/Bioinf/data/bioinf-data/Papenfuss_lab/projects/ginerg_papenfuss_lab/Github_projects/SDiepstraten_2021_05_14/fastqfiles/", pattern="*_R2")
bam <- sub("\\.fastq.gz",".bam",basename(R1))
mm10 <- "/stornext/General/data/academic/lab_smyth/smyth/Genome/UCSC/mm10"
Mapping_results <- align(mm10,R1,R2,output_file=bam,useAnnotation=TRUE,annot.inbuilt="mm10",nthreads=16,sortReadsByCoordinates=TRUE)
save(file = "Mapping_results.RData", Mapping_results)
print(sessionInfo())
sink()
> writeLines(readLines("./scripts/02_featurecount.R"))
setwd("/stornext/Bioinf/data/bioinf-data/Papenfuss_lab/projects/ginerg_papenfuss_lab/Github_projects/SDiepstraten_2021_05_14/B_ALL_RNA-Seq_from_Ashley/subjunc_bamfiles")
date <- Sys.Date()
sink(paste0(date, "-featurecount.log"), split = TRUE)
library(BiocVersion) # load this to view the version in sessionInfo
library(Rsubread)
BAM <- dir(pattern=".BAM$")
fc <- featureCounts(BAM, annot.inbuilt = "mm10", isPairedEnd = TRUE)
propmap <- propmapped(BAM)
ann <- getInBuiltAnnotation("mm10")
out.gene <- list(count = fc, propmap = propmap, ann = ann)
save(out.gene, file = paste0(date, "-B_ALL_RNA-Seq_from_Ashley-rsubread-mm10-gene.RData"))
print(sessionInfo())
sink()

2.2 Checking the number of mapped reads

Here we plot the number of successfully mapped reads and the proportion of mapped reads. As shown below, the proportion of successfully mapped reads are above 97% and the average library size is ~28 million.

> load("./RData/EÂµ-Myc-dCas9a-SAM_RNASeq.RData")
> propmap <- out.gene$propmap
> propmap$Name <- rownames(propmap)
> ggplot(data = propmap, aes(x = reorder(Name, PropMapped), y = PropMapped)) + geom_bar(stat = "identity",
+     fill = "#FF9999") + theme_minimal() + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90,
+     hjust = 0.95, vjust = 0.2)) + ggtitle("Proportion of mapped reads") + xlab("") +
+     ylab("")
> ggplot(data = propmap, aes(x = reorder(Name, NumMapped), y = NumMapped)) + geom_bar(stat = "identity",
+     fill = "#FF9999") + theme_minimal() + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90,
+     hjust = 0.95, vjust = 0.2)) + ggtitle("Number of mapped reads") + xlab("") +
+     ylab("")

2.3 Annotation

Mouse genome annotation on the gene level is obtained from Rsubread and annotation for each Entrez Gene ID is obtained from the most up to date NCBI Mus_muculus.gene_info file.

> d <- out.gene
> ann <- d$count$annotation
> ann$Chr <- unlist(lapply(strsplit(ann$Chr, ";"), function(x) paste(unique(x), collapse = ",")))
> ann$Strand <- ann$Start <- ann$End <- NULL
> ann$Length <- ann$Length
> ncbi.file <- "indices/Mus_musculus.gene_info"
> ncbi.L1 <- readLines(ncbi.file, n = 1)
> ncbi.colname <- unlist(strsplit(substring(ncbi.L1, 9, 240), "\t"))
> ncbi <- read.delim(ncbi.file, skip = 1, head = F, stringsAsFactors = F, quote = "")
> ncbi <- ncbi[, -1]
> colnames(ncbi) <- ncbi.colname
> m <- match(ann$GeneID, ncbi$GeneID)
> ann$Symbol <- ncbi$Symbol[m]
> ann$Type <- ncbi$type_of_gene[m]
> ann$Description <- ncbi$description[m]
> head(ann)
> counts <- d$count$counts
> d <- DGEList(counts, genes = ann[, c("Symbol", "Chr", "Length", "Description", "Type")])
> rownames(d$counts) <- d$genes$Symbol
> dim(d)

2.4 Creating the DGEList object

First we create a new DGEList object, which includes information about read counts for each gene, sample information and gene annotations. The new DGEList object has 27179 genes and 18 samples.

> d$samples$SampleNo <- strsplit2(rownames(d$samples), "_")[, 1]
> d <- d[, order(as.numeric(d$samples$SampleNo))]
> Targets <- read.csv("Targets.csv")
> d$samples$Type <- Targets$Type[1:18]
> d$samples$Subtype <- Targets$Subtype[1:18]
> d$samples$BioRep <- Targets$Biorep[1:18]
> dim(d)
> save(d, file = "./RData/DHL_DGEList.RData")

6.2 Deciding the design of the experiment and Estimating dispersion and BCV plot

Next we define the design matrix based on the experimental design. Then we estimate the dispersion between biological replicates.

> Experiment <- factor(d$samples$Subtype, levels = c("WT", "BCL2_1", "BCL2_2", "NTC",
+     "MEFs"))
> design <- model.matrix(~Experiment)
> d <- estimateDisp(d, design = design)
> d$common.dispersion
[1] 0.0688

The square root of the common dispersion gives the coefficient of variation of biological variation. Here the common dispersion is found to be 0.0688, so the coefficient of biological variation is around 0.262. The dispersion estimates can be viewed in a BCV plot:

> plotBCV(d)

The biological coefficient of variation (BCV) plots show the BCV for each gene.
